node.text:
A police raid in Brazil saved the most detailed pterosaur fossil yet! 
​
​The incredibly well-preserved flying lizard, Tupandactylus navigans, sported a ridiculously large head crest - so big it would have had trouble flying long distances with it. Read more about this ancient beast through the link in our bio ➡️ @ScienceAlert.
​
​📷 Sergey Krasovskiy/Stocktrek/Getty Images

Some parts of space are all wrinkly! 😮 
​
These roiling clouds of gas are scrunched together by the turbulence of star formation. The densest spinning knots in the resulting wrinkles collapse under their own gravity and ignite into stars themselves. ✨ 
​
​In nurseries as dense as this one called Ophiuchus, some of the stars will burst into life and then die rapidly, producing the heavier radioactive elements. Researchers believe this is how our solar system was birthed and you can read more about the process through the link in our bio ➡️ @ScienceAlert.
​
​📷 João Alves/ESO VISIONS

Did you know that not all frogs eye shapes look the same? 🐸 
​
​Scientists have discovered there's seven distinct types of frog eye shapes that evolved at least 116 times! Swipe to see some of the different versions. 
​
​1️⃣ 📷: Paul Souders/Getty Images
​2️⃣ 📷: Cervino et al.,Proceedings of the Royal Society B, 2021

Mars or Earth? 🌍
​
​ 
​
This is a beautiful photo of the Sahara Desert taken by astronaut Shane Kimbrough on the International Space Station. It might have been taken in space, but it's definitely an image of Earth. 
​
​You might think that astronauts take a lot of photos of the Sahara, but there's good reason for that! With an area of 9,200,000 square kilometers (3,600,000 sq mi), it's the largest hot desert in the world - smaller only than the Arctic and Antarctica. 
​
​📷: Shane Kimbrough/@NASA
​
​

node.text:
That is a 'mini brain' that developed proto-eyes.... 👀 
​
​On tiny, human-derived brain organoids grown in dishes, two bilaterally symmetrical optic cups were seen to grow, mirroring the development of eye structures in human embryos. Although we're not gonna lie this is pretty creepy, this incredible result will help us to better understand the process of eye differentiation and development, as well as eye diseases. 
​
​Read more about this discovery at the link in our bio ➡️@ScienceAlert 
​
​📷: Elke Gabriel

While we still don't know if nuclear fusion is a feasible source of future power, scientists have recently broken another record in our attempts to make it a reality - creating the biggest blast of energy yet, but only for a 100 trillionth of a second.
​
​This colorized image shows the ignition of deuterium-titium implosions of inertial confinement fusion.
​
​ 📷: Don Jedlovec

node.text:
These weird insect relatives scuttled along Earth's ocean floor in search for tasty carrion or prey, ​530 to 252 million years ago. 🏹 
​
While Trilobites all had a three-part shell, different species evolved all sorts of weird spikes or even eye stalks and they left behind a rich fossil record of shells and trackways. 
​
​This one, Cheirurus ingricus, was found in what's now Russia. It lived in during the Middle Ordovician period. 
​
​ 📷 @smithsoniannmnh

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by ScienceAlert on August 21, 2021. May be an image of xray and text that says 'COVID19 with vaccine COVID19 without vaccine @JesseOSheaMD'.

node.text:
​While vaccines don't stop all COVID-19 cases, they make a massive difference to its severity, as exemplified by these lung x-rays shared by MD Jesse O’Shea.
​
​Top: a 47-year-old man without known comorbidities who received one Pfizer vaccine and developed COVID-19 2 weeks after. While he had a runny nose, mild body aches, and mild cough, his chest X ray is relatively normal.
​
​Bottom: a 50-year-old active female patient developed lung damage (all the fluffy white bits that oxygen can no longer reach) and required the greatest amount of life support available, after contracting COVID-19 while unvaccinated.
​
​"Vaccines are ~95% effective at preventing case 2 from happening. Of course there are also mild cases of COVID in unvaccinated Individuals," explained O’Shea.
​
​📷 @jesseosheamd

A spectacular galactic merger flings winds emitting radio waves into the Universe💥
​
​These details were captured using 70,000 radio antennas spread across Europe, allowing astronomers to achieve a resolution never seen before for such distant galaxies.
​
​Read more through the link in our bio ➡️ @ScienceAlert.

😱 This deadly jellyfish died with its last meal still intact!
​
Juvenile fish, like this one trapped here, often use jellyfish as protection from predators. But sometimes this strategy goes awry, and this one ended up as lunch for the compass jellyfish (Chrysaora hysoscella),
​
